Ed - Let me say that I have not forgotten those things that you have written in the recent past. What had got to me was the anger vented towards the &quot;government&quot;. I had to think quite a bit on this. The only response that I have is to ask if there were anything or any action that you took that you found personally reprehensible. <br><br>
I spent quite some time in Cambodia. I spent quite some time in 'Nam. And I can honestly say that I cannot think of one thing that I was involved in that I am sorry for. The weapons caches in Cambodia and Loas that were recovered I know saved many lives of both American and ARVN's. The hurt that we inflicted on Chuck during the incursions also saved many lives. I cannot possibly see that anything that you did could have caused any harm other than to Charley. I believe that everything that you had done had saved lives.<br><br>
I also want to ask: when has any government/military been totally forthright about battle plans?<br><br>
I am not sorry that we crossed the borders. We had uncovered caches, food, weapons and military goods that would have caused us and the S. Vietnamese great harm.<br><br>
I had this article sitting on my desk for many days reflecting on whether or not I should posts these passages. While I had my own personal reasons for posting them, I did so, for a large part, for you.
